metadata.name: Linear Cycle #188
metadata.description:
This piece captures the essence of life's journey. The artwork features a mesmerizing interplay of linear patterns and shapes, a visual representation of the eternal cycle of birth and rebirth. 
It is a digital creation, made with unique and fascinating algorithm precision. 
An invitation to ponder the cyclical patterns of the universe, to reflect on the never-ending dance of life and death. 
It is a final depiction of the creative process, a digital symphony of art and technology that is both captivating and thought-provoking.

metadata.name: Wild Palms #87
metadata.description:
When I was a child walking with my father in the park, he once told me if I could hear the trees talking to each other. I listened, and in the noise of the leaves and seeds in the wind, I truly recognized their languages and voices. I was so overwhelmed by the depth and diversity of the world and the creatures that inhabit it, that it is still one of my most vivid memories. 

When I walk through parks or forests, I always listen to what they say. It is unlikely that I will ever be able to engage in their dialogue, but it is always like a touch of the magical immensity of life.

Wild Palms is the name of a gallery of our friends with whom it is always a pleasure to talk in the language of humans, and they have a garden right in the gallery.
In the project we mix childhood memories and friendship, the aesthetics of woodcuts, Polaroid and hand-printed photos with echoes of the digital voice of our present.

Thanks to YulikolaY for getting the code ready for production.

Made with love, AI and p5.js code

January, 2023

metadata.name: Mornings #13
metadata.description:
... a photograph taken at morning on a film camera somewhere in the American Midwest. The sun is present enough to light the sky, but still remains below the horizon leaving the land slightly underexposed and the trees nearly silhouetted ...

---

My journey continues to make the most compelling landscapes I can spring from a text editor. I spent a lot of time examining painted as well as traditional digital art landscapes, both of which are incredibly mature mediums. Paint, in particular, seems to be completely mastered - with some artist's work leaving nothing to be desired. What I have seen in digital has also blown me away. I want to work towards the bar set by these artists and marry their aesthetic prowess with the power, variety, and excitement of generative art.

--

// Technical Notes
-The render will take ~2-3 minutes.

-Default resolution is 3000x6000 px (including letterbox). While it's possible to render at any resolution, this is my intended resolution for the project - the product of an artistic choice to make the piece behave more like a photograph. This limited (but still high) resolution gives the features at the smallest scales some fuzziness, giving a sense that detail extends below the resolution of the piece. I think this imparts a more natural aesthetic as opposed to the perfect forms and edges of canvas shapes.


// Controls
Press "z" to zoom in, and take a look around. Keys "1", "2", "3", and "4" to control the zoom amount.

Press "s" to download the image. Right-click-save will not work.


// Owners
Token owners will have access to artist prints. Send me a DM on twitter.

metadata.name: Nullteilung #112
metadata.description:
Nullteilung is another exercise in suprematism and composition. Born from a series of exercises in subdevision and tesselation, it seeks to connect with the user through the creation of a sense of order and balance in the composition.

The term "Nullteilung" a German word that can be translated to "zero division" which is suggesative of the order and disorder paramount in the piece, working toward a goal of emotional and programmatic purity.

metadata.name: Composition study : Grid #233
metadata.description: This project explores the use of geometric shapes, specifically grids, cubes, and patterns, in composition. The focus will be on using these shapes and patterns to create dynamic and visually interesting compositions, both in 2D and 3D forms. The project begins by studying the use of grids and how they can be used to create structure and balance in a composition. Next, the use of cubes will be examined, and how they can be used to add depth and dimension to a composition. Finally, the project will delve into the use of patterns and how they can be used to create movement and interest within a composition.
